{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583365"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:14:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:14:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2667"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2667"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.01,0.38,0.12,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51032"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2667"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36276"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"480"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42541"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51032"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health review. He has a medical history of hypertension and atrial fibrillation. His regular medications are perindopril, amlodipine, apixaban, and amiodarone. He has no known allergies. He does not smoke and exercises regularly. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The patient is advised that certain investigations should be undertaken every six months to monitor for potential drug adverse effects.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important investigation for monitoring purposes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Renal function tests","Lipid studies","Thyroid function tests","Liver function tests","Coagulation studies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question focuses on the importance of monitoring for adverse effects in patients on long-term medication, particularly amiodarone. \u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are the most important investigation for monitoring in this case. Amiodarone, an antiarrhythmic medication used for atrial fibrillation, has several long-term effects and requires regular monitoring. The most common long-term adverse effect of amiodarone is hypothyroidism, occurring in 2-4% of cases. This is due to the high iodine content in amiodarone, which can damage the thyroid gland. Regular thyroid function tests are essential to detect this complication early.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are important for monitoring patients on ACE inhibitors like perindopril, especially initially. However, since this patient has been stable on perindopril for many years, regular monitoring is less critical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipid studies\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful for general cardiovascular risk assessment but are not specific for monitoring medication toxicity in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver function tests\u003C/strong\u003E can be affected by amiodarone, but hepatotoxicity rarely progresses to liver cirrhosis. While these tests may be part of the monitoring protocol, they are less crucial than thyroid function tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulation studies\u003C/strong\u003E are not routinely needed for monitoring apixaban therapy. Unlike warfarin, direct oral anticoagulants like apixaban do not require regular coagulation monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that while not mentioned in the options, chest X-rays are also recommended every six months for patients on amiodarone to monitor for pulmonary toxicity, which is the most serious adverse effect, occurring in 2% of cases and carrying a 10% mortality rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while multiple investigations may be part of a comprehensive monitoring plan for this patient, thyroid function tests are the most important due to the high prevalence and potential severity of amiodarone-induced thyroid dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Long-term amiodarone use has several adverse effects, most commonly hypothyroidism.","Regular thyroid function tests are essential for monitoring patients on amiodarone therapy.","Amiodarone can cause pulmonary toxicity, which requires monitoring with chest X-rays every six months."],"references":["Park HS, Kim YN. Adverse effects of long-term amiodarone therapy. Korean J Intern Med. 2014;29(5):571-73. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4164718/","Amiodarone. In: Australian Medicines Handbook [online]. Cited 2021 Jul 8. Available at: https://amhonline.amh.net.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36276"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2667"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36276"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-20T12:23:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-20T12:23:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item"